Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever - Afghanistan 19980509.0911
Date: Sun 17 Sep 2000 14:36:33 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Reuters 17 Sep 2000 [edited

Iran Bans Transportation of Fever Animals
------------------------------------------
Iran's veterinary officials have banned the transportation of livestock
from the southeast to the rest of the country after an outbreak of a deadly
fever. The deadly Crimean-Congo Hemorrhagic Fever (CCHF), which has killed
6 people in southeastern Iran this summer, is acquired from bites by ticks
carried by domestic animals.
The daily [newspaper Kayhan said livestock smuggled into Iran from
Afghanistan have infected Iranian animals, which have in turn infected
humans. [Actually, it is infected ticks (infected by biting the animals)
biting the people, not the animals. - Mod.TG
Seven people remain symptomatic and in hospitals.
More than 300 000 domesticated animals have been smuggled into Iran through
the country's eastern borders between March and August 2000, a veterinary
official said during a scientific seminar on the disease in the
southeastern city of Zahedan. "More than 400 000 animals...have been
sprayed [for ticks in the last 2 months since the symptoms of the fever
were first spotted in the province," Ali Asghar Baraee-nejad said.
CCHF causes extensive liver damage resulting in jaundice and even death in
humans. Animal carriers are not affected.
The fever killed 14 people in eastern Iran last year.
